[[File:The wedding night.png|thumb|A satirical cartoon by [[Isaac Cruikshank]] of [[Charlotte, Princess Royal|Princess Charlotte]] and [[Frederick I of Württemberg|Prince Frederick]] being led to bed by a party including her parents, [[King George III]] and [[Queen Charlotte]]]]

The '''bedding ceremony''' refers to the [[wedding]] custom of putting the [[newlywed]] couple together in the marital bed before numerous witnesses, thereby completing the [[marriage]]. In most traditions the newlyweds were put in bed by their family, friends, and neighbors.

The purpose of the ritual was to establish the [[consummation]] of the marriage, either by actually witnessing the couple's first [[sexual intercourse]] or symbolically, by leaving before consummation. It symbolized the [[community]]'s involvement in the marriage. The legally binding nature of the ceremony varied greatly from place to place and through time.

==Traditions==
[[File:Brauysegen im Bett.gif|thumb|Reymont and Melusina blessed by the bishop in their bed on their wedlock, 15th-century woodcut]]
[[File:Carl X Gustav of Sweden & Hedwig Eleanor of Sweden c 1654 by Juriaen Ovens.jpg|thumb|After the wedding in 1654 between [[Charles X Gustav of Sweden]] and [[Hedvig Eleonora of Holstein-Gottorp]].]]

Bedding rituals have been practiced in various cultures, the ceremony differing from place to place. The people putting the newlyweds in bed have usually included their family, friends and wider community.{{sfn|Bailey|Barclay|2017|p=44}} The ritual is often associated with music, bawdy songs and jokes. It symbolised the community's involvement in the marriage and especially in the couple's [[sexual intimacy]], but also their [[marital fidelity]]. The consummation itself, i.e. the couple's first [[sexual intercourse]], was not witnessed in most of [[Western Europe]].{{sfn|Bailey|Barclay|2017|p=45}}

In England, the ceremony usually began with a priest [[Christian blessing|blessing]] the bed, after which the newlyweds prepared themselves for bed and drank [[sweet wine|sweet]] and [[spicy wine]]. The [[groomsmen]] and the [[bridesmaid]]s then sat on the sides of the bed and threw the couple's [[stocking]]s at them; a hit was believed to indicate that the thrower would soon marry. Finally the curtains were drawn around the bed and the couple were left alone. Some newlyweds refused to take part in the bedding ceremony. [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] of England ({{reign|1625|1649}}) notably barred the door of his bedroom; however, despite his rejection, the custom remained prevalent for another century among all social classes, including the royal family.{{sfn|Monger|2004|p=23}}{{refn|The bedding ritual was fully observed at the wedding of [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]]'s niece and nephew, [[Mary II of England|Mary]] and [[William III of England|William]], with the King himself drawing the curtains.{{sfn|Monger|2004|p=24}}|group=nb}}

In the 16th century, in what is now Germany, the bedding ceremony was performed to the sound of [[Pipe (instrument)|pipes]], [[drums]] and "obscene noises", after which the couple were left alone and the guests continued celebrating loudly enough for the newlyweds not to be heard. In many places, the newlyweds were dressed for bed separately by their family or community and then led to the bedroom.{{sfn|Bailey|Barclay|2017|p=44}} In others, the couple were expected to rejoin the party afterwards.{{sfn|Korpiolla|2009|p=61}} During the [[Reformation era]], the bedding ceremony was associated with rituals that assigned socioeconomic rights and duties to the bride as [[housewife]].{{sfn|Bailey|Barclay|2017|p=45}}

In [[Scandinavia]], it was the most distinguished wedding guest who led the bride to bed in a festive procession.{{refn|The [[Mayor of Stockholm]] led the bride {{circa}} 1416. In 1528, the Swedish king [[Gustav Vasa]] performed the role at the wedding of his trusted servant.{{sfn|Korpiolla|2009|p=61}}|group=nb}} After putting them in bed, the guests offered dishes to the couple and quickly ate with them before leaving them alone. Due to the ritual's importance, specially decorated wedding beds were sometimes borrowed from friends, family or neighbours. The bedding eventually became merely symbolic, with the bride's parents covering the newlyweds with a blanket and then uncovering them.{{sfn|Korpiolla|2009|p=61}}

==Legal consequences==
The original purpose of the bedding ceremony was to establish the [[consummation]] of the marriage, without which the union could be [[annulled]]. The legally binding nature of the ritual was unclear to many, particularly to lower classes. One marriage in Britain was annulled on the pretext that the bride had run away within 15 minutes of the ritual, and in another case, a clandestine marriage was made public when the pregnant wife shared her husband's deathbed.{{sfn|Stone|1992|p=22}} Public bedding in 18th-century Britain was widely believed to give additional legitimacy to the marriage.{{sfn|Stone|1992|p=163}} In Scotland, although marriage was formed by simple consent and required no formalities or consummation,{{sfn|Bailey|Barclay|2017|p=47}} the bedding rituals were widespread but unstructured; a couple simply wanted someone to see them in bed together. A couple could also be pressured into marriage in this way: a person stumbling upon an unmarried couple in bed could pronounce them man and wife on the spot.{{sfn|Bailey|Barclay|2017|p=48}}

In medieval Scandinavia, the bedding ceremony was of great legal importance. Laws in many [[Swedish province]]s regarded public bedding as essential to the completion of a marriage,{{sfn|Korpiolla|2009|p=60}} but the legal importance later diminished due to new royal laws.{{sfn|Korpiolla|2009|p=61}} In Iceland, a marriage was only valid if it included the bedding ritual witnessed by at least six men.{{sfn|Korpiolla|2009|p=62}}

In the case of royal marriages, the ceremony took on added significance.

==In popular culture==
The bedding ritual has featured in popular culture for centuries. It has been hinted at in ''The Penny Wedding'', an 1818 painting by [[David Wilkie (artist)|David Wilkie]], and possibly also in the homonymous 1819 painting by [[Alexander Carse]]. Numerous songs also make references to the ceremony.{{sfn|Bailey|Barclay|2017|p=47}}

{{poemquote
