d evidence which showed his innocence, and overturned his conviction.<ref name="2005 HCA 68">{{cite AustLII|HCA|68|2005|litigants=Mallard v The Queen |parallelcite=(2005) 224 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 125 |date=15 November 2009 |courtname=auto}}.</ref> As such, Mallard was released from prison. A "cold case" review of the murder conducted after Mallard's release implicated one Simon Rochford as the actual offender and Mallard was exonerated. |}
===Canada=== {{Main|Overturned convictions in Canada}} {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Date of crime ! Defendant(s) ! Crime ! Location ! Sentence ! Time served ! Legally exonerated ! Notes |- |September 1990 |[[James Driskell]] |Murder of Perry Harder |[[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] |Life in prison |12 years |No |Harder was murdered by being shot several times in the chest and buried in a shallow grave near some railroad tracks. Police suspected Driskell of the murders because Harder implicated Driskell in a series of break-ins. The prosecution presented three hairs from Driskell's van that they argued belonged to Harder. A later review by the Forensic Science Services in England determined that none of the hairs belonged to Harder. It was later discovered that a key police witness, Ray Zanidean, tried to recant his testimony. In exchange for his testimony, police made a deal with Zanidean that he would not be charged in an arson case. He also received payment for his legal fees and received money for mortgage payments that were in arrears. He also received $20,000 payment. This information was not disclosed to the jury. Although he has not been formally exonerated, he was released on Nov. 24, 2003.<ref name=Driskell>{{cite news|title=James Driskell|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news2/background/driskell/|accessdate=29 April 2015|agency=CBC News|date=July 18, 2006}}</ref> |- |June 19, 1990 |[[Robert Baltovich]] |Murder of his girlfriend, Elizabeth Bain |Scarborough, Ontario, Canada. |Life |11 years |Yes |[[Robert Baltovich]] was convicted in 1992 of the murder of Elizabeth Bain; released in 2000 to prepare an appeal based on new evidence. The [[Court of Appeal for Ontario]] ordered a new trial, which began in March 2008. At the outset of the trial, the Crown declined to call any evidence, and the judge ordered the jury to bring a verdict of not guilty. Circumstantial evidence pointed to the serial killer [[Paul Bernardo]], an acquaintance of Ms Bain's, as the murderer. The Ontario Attorney-General denied financial compensation to Baltovich in 2010. |- |May 28, 1971 |[[Donald Marshall, Jr.]] |Murder of Sandy Seale |[[Sydney, Nova Scotia]] |Life imprisonment |11 years |Yes |Donald Marshall and Sandy Seale, then both 17 years old, had been walking around Wentworth Park in [[Sydney, Nova Scotia]] during the late evening with the intent to "roll a drunk" as stated at Marshall's trial. They confronted an older man they encountered in the park named Roy Ebsary. Seale was stabbed to death. Police speculated that Marshall had murdered Seale and he was convicted on the basis of witness statements.<ref name="New York Times">{{Cite news|title=Donald Marshall Jr., Symbol of Bias, Dies at 55|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/07/world/americas/07marshall.html|publisher=The New York Times|last=Grimes|first=William|date=2009-08-06|accessdate=6 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Acquitted in killing, Marshall is jubilant|work=The Globe and Mail|date=11 May 1983}}</ref> Several years later, a witness came forward to say he had seen another man stab Seale, and several prior witness statements pinpointing Marshall were recanted. A year after the appeal, the Nova Scotia Court of Appeal declared him not guilty of the murder. In its ruling, however, the court opined that Marshall was “the author of his own misfortune”, essentially blaming him for the conviction.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ebsary is found guilty in slaying that cost another man 11 years|work=The Globe and Mail|date=9 November 1983}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/society/crime-justice/general-3/donald-marshall-exonerated-of-wrongful-conviction.html "Donald Marshall exonerated of wrongful conviction"]. CBC Archives, 26 January 1990. Retrieved 16 June 2014.</ref><ref name="danielnpaul">{{cite web|url=http://www.danielnpaul.com/DonaldMarshallJr.-1971.html|website=danielnpaul.com|title=Donald Marshall Jr: 1971 Wrongful Murder Conviction |accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://www.indigenousbar.ca/cases/marshallinq.htm "Nova Scotia (Attorney-General) v. Nova Scotia (Royal Commission Into Marshall Presecution), 1989, 2 S.C.R. 788"]. Retrieved 16 June 2014.</ref>
A 1990 royal commission of inquiry criticized that finding as “a serious and fundamental error", blaming police incompetence and “systemic racism” for the conviction (Marshall is [[Mi’kmaq]]). His case led to widespread changes in Canada's evidence disclosure rules. Prosecutors had withheld exculpatory evidence from the defense in the Marshall case; the prosecution must now fully disclose to the defense any evidence it has in its possession. Ebsary was subsequently tried and convicted of manslaughter.<ref name="New York Times"/> |- |January 31, 1969 |[[David Milgaard]] |Murder of 20-year-old nursing student, Gail Miller |[[Saskatoon, Saskatchewan]] |Life in Prison |23 years |Yes |In 1969, 16-year-old [[David Milgaard]] was convicted and given a life sentence for the murder of 20-year-old nursing aide Gail Miller. After 23 years of imprisonment, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] allowed for the release of Milgaard. In 1997 Milgaard, received an apology from the Saskatchewan government after DNA tests in the U.K. excluded him.<ref name=Milgaard>{{cite news|last1=wood|first1=Michael|title=Milgaard charged with assault, uttering threats|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/10/26/david-milgaard-arrested-on-domestic-charges|agency=Toronto Sun|date=October 26, 2011}}</ref> |- |October 3, 1984 |[[Guy Paul Morin]] |Rape and murder of his 9 year old neighbour, Christine Jessop |[[Queensville, Ontario]] |Life in prison |3 years |Yes |On 3 October 1984, Jessop disappeared after being dropped off by the school bus at her home.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|title = For Janet Jessop, October is a time to mourn murdered daughter Christine all over again|date = 15 August 2012|url = https://www.thestar.com/news/crime/2012/08/15/for_janet_jessop_october_is_a_time_to_mourn_murdered_daughter_christine_all_over_again.html|last = Rush|first = Curtis}}</ref> Her body was discovered on December 31, nearly three months later. She had been sexually assaulted and murdered.<ref name=":1">{{cite news|url = http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/society/crime-justice/cold-cases-unsolved-crimes-in-canada/christine-jessop-queensville-ont-1984.html|title = Cold Cases: Christine Jessop, Queensville, Ont. (1984)|accessdate = 6 February 2014|website = CBC Digital Archives}}</ref> Morin was arrested for Jessop's murder in April 1985 and was acquitted.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OxgiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_KUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5114,2939925|title=Appeal planned|date=6 March 1986|work=Montreal Gazette|page=B–1|accessdate=16 August 2010}}</ref> The [[Crown attorney|Crown]] exercised its right to appeal the [[verdict]] on the grounds that the trial judge made a fundamental error prejudicing the Crown's right to a fair trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-9YyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pu8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=3062,2335594|title=Crown to appeal Morin's acquittal|date=6 March 1986|work=Ottawa Citizen|page=A–12|accessdate=16 August 2010}}</ref> In 1987 the [[List of Canadian courts of appeal|Court of Appeal]] ordered a new trial.<ref name="King">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacdl.org/public.nsf/championarticles/19980808?opendocument |title=The Ordeal of Guy Paul Morin: Canada Copes With Systemic Injustice |last=King |first=Jack |date=August 1988 |work=Champion Magazine |publisher=National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers |accessdate=16 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s2AJbWDF?url=http://www.nacdl.org/public.nsf/championarticles/19980808?opendocument |archivedate=16 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> In 1992, Morin was convicted at his second trial and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/news/local/article/26005--canadian-cases-of-wrongful-conviction |title=Canadian Cases Of Wrongful Conviction |date=31 January 2007 |work=CityNews |publisher=Rogers Broadcasting |accessdate=16 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s2BTxojR?url=http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/news/local/article/26005--canadian-cases-of-wrongful-conviction |archivedate=16 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Improvements in [[DNA]] testing led to a test in 1995 which excluded Morin as the murderer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/11/world/queensville-journal-jailed-in-killing-he-s-guilty-only-of-being-a-misfit.html |title=Queensville Journal; Jailed in Killing, He's Guilty Only of Being a Misfit |last=Farnsworth |first=Clyde H. |date=11 April 1995 |work=The New York Times |page=4 |accessdate=16 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s2C5DQ15?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/11/world/queensville-journal-jailed-in-killing-he-s-guilty-only-of-being-a-misfit.html |archivedate=16 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Morin's appeal of his conviction was [[Appeal#How an appeal is processed|allowed]] (i.e., the conviction was reversed), and a [[directed verdict]] of acquittal entered in the appeal.<ref name="King" />
An inquiry culminating in the [[Kaufman Report]] into Morin's case also uncovered evidence of police and prosecutorial misconduct, and of misrepresentation of forensic evidence by the [[Ontario Centre of Forensic Sciences]].<ref name="King" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/1998/04/09/morin980409c.html |title=Morin inquiry slams investigation |date=13 November 1998 |work=[[CBC.ca]] |accessdate=16 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s2CWwlgM?url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/1998/04/09/morin980409c.html |archivedate=16 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Christine Jessop's murderer is still unknown. |- |August 9, 1967 |[[Romeo Phillion]] |Murder of Leopold Roy |[[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]] |Life in prison |31 years |Yes |Murder of veteran of fire department Leopold Roy<ref name=Moldaver>{{cite news|last1=Moldaver|first1=J.A.|title=Her Majesty the Queen Respondent and Romeo Joseph Phillion|url=http://www.ontariocourts.on.ca/decisions/2009/march/2009ONCA0202.pdf|agency=Court of Appeal for Ontario|date=March 2009}}</ref> Phillion died in 2015 at the age of 76 before his $14&nbsp;million lawsuit against the Ontario governmenthad been settled. The longest ever sentence served by a Canadian prisoner whose conviction was later overturned. |- |December 23, 1981 |[[Thomas Sophonow]] |Murder of 16-year-old Barbara Stoppel | | | | |Stoppel was working at the Ideal Donut Shop in Winnipeg when she was found strangled in the restroom with a nylon cord. She died 5 days later. Witnesses gave police a description of a man wearing a cowboy hat enter the establishment, lock the door, and walk towards the back. Sophonow, who had a police record, bore a resemblance to the sketch. He was convicted on the basis of the eyewitness identification and a jailhouse informant who testified that Sophonow confessed to him. Sophonow was tried three times. The first ended in a mistrial, the second two in convictions. Both convictions were overturned and the court of appeal ordered an acquittal. The Winnipeg police service began a reinvestigation and in June 2000, they publicly announced that Sophonow was innocent and another suspect had been identified. In 2001, Justice Peter Cory concluded that police misconduct contributed to the wrongful conviction. The use of jailhouse informants and misuse and manipulation of eye witness accounts was criticized.<ref name=Rossmo>{{cite book|last1=Rossmo|first1=D. Kim|title=Criminal Investigative Failures|date=December 15, 2008|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=1420047515|pages=299–300|edition=1}}</ref> |- |June 9, 1959 |[[Steven Truscott]] |rape and murder of classmate Lynne Harper |[[Vanastra]], [[Ontario]] |Death, then Life in Prison |10 years |Yes |Steven Truscott's wrongful conviction of murder in the death of [[Lynne Harper]] stood for 48 years before finally being overturned August 28, 2007. |- |October 9, 1993 |[[Tammy Marquardt]] |Murder of her son, Kenneth* |[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] |Life in prison. |14 |Yes |Tammy was home with her 2½ years old son Kenneth who was napping in their spare bedroom. When she checked on him, she found him tangled in the sheets and gasping for breath. Kenneth suffered irreparable brain damage and was taken off life support three days later. Dr. [[Charles Randal Smith|Charles Smith]], who was considered to be the leading expert in Canada on criminally suspicious pediatric deaths, was consulted on the case. Smith concluded that Kenneth's death was not accidental. Tammy's defense insisted her son died from complications of an epileptic seizure. She was convicted.
Smith's work subsequently came into question on a number of cases. On June 7, 2005, Chief Coroner for Ontario, Dr. Barry McLellan, announced that a formal review would be conducted of criminal cases for which Smith had performed the autopsy.
In October 2007, another forensic pathologist assigned to the case concluded that Smith's finding of asphyxia was “illogical and completely against scientific evidence-based reasoning.” In 2011, the Ontario Court of Appeal quashed her conviction and the Crown withdrew the charges against Tammy. Experts hired by the prosecution agreed that [[Sudden Unexpected Death in Epilepsy]] (SUDEP) could not be ruled out as the cause of death in Kenneth's case as well as other natural cases of death.<ref name=Marquardt>{{cite news|title=Tammy Marquardt|url=http://www.aidwyc.org/cases/historical/tammy-marquardt/|accessdate=30 April 2015|agency=The Association in Defence of the Wrongly Convicted}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Real Justice: Branded a Baby Killer: The Story of Tammy Marquardt|last=D'Costa|first=Jasmine|publisher=James Lorimer & Company|year=2015|isbn=9781459409934|location=|pages=}}</ref> |- |December 14, 1961 |[[Réjean Hinse]] |Armed robbery of a general store |[[Mont-Laurier, Quebec]] |15 years |8 years |Yes |Claimed he was 200&nbsp;km away in Montreal at the time of the robbery. The Quebec Police Commission concluded in 1989 that Hinse was the victim of "a botched investigation." Acquitted by the Supreme Court of Canada in 1997 and paid C$13.1&nbsp;million by the Quebec and Federal Governments - the largest wrongful conviction award in Canadian history. |}
=== China === {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Date of crime ! Defendant(s) ! Crime ! Location ! Sentence ! Time served ! Legally exonerated ! Notes |- |1987 |[[Wrongful execution#Teng|Teng Xingshan]] |Rape, robbery and murder |Hunan, China |Death sentence |Executed |Yes |Teng Xingshan, a butcher, was convicted (the court was told "Teng confessed his crime on his initiative and his confession conforms with scientific inspection and identification") and executed in 1989 for the murder of Shi Xiaorong, a waitress who had disappeared. Shi reappeared in Shandong in 2005 and said she had never met Teng. Teng was posthumously acquitted in 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/05/chinas-reappearing-murder-victims/|title=China’s Reappearing Murder Victims|last=Hunwick|first=Robert Foyle|date=2014-05-08|work=|newspaper=The Diplomat|access-date=7 October 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.executedtoday.com/2015/01/28/1989-teng-xingshan-butcher/|title=1989: Teng Xingshan, butcher|date=2015-01-28|website=ExecutedToday.com|access-date=7 October 2016}}</ref> |- |1995 |[[Wrongful execution#Nie|Nie Shubin]] |Rape and murder |Zhang Ying village, Hubei province |Death sentence |Executed |Yes |Nie Shubin was convicted after the police had obtained a confession from him with a week of "...skillful interrogation, including psychological warfare..." and executed in 1995 for the rape and murder of Kang Juhua, a woman in her thirties. In 2005, Wang Shujin admitted to the police that he had committed the murder and described murder scene details only known to the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.executedtoday.com/2009/04/27/1995-nie-shubin-oops/|title=1995: Nie Shubin. Oops.|last=|first=|date=2009-04-27|website=Executed Today|publisher=|access-date=7 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uscnpm.org/blog/2016/06/10/exclusive-can-china-save-nie-shubins-innocence/|title=Exclusive: Can China Save Nie Shubin’s Innocence? »|last=Morris|first=Willia