old's lawyer said that former Detective Chief Inspector James Harrison-Griffiths was told in 1976 by Commander Bert Wickstead of the Metropolitan Police that the apparent first victim, Terry Eve - by then a missing person - was alive and living in west London.<ref name="liar" /><ref name="lifer">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/oct/27/prisonsandprobation.ukcrime|title=Lifer's 23-year fight to clear his name|last=Muir|first=Hugh|date=27 October 2003|work=The Guardian|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> [[Lord Woolf]], with [[Richard Aikens|Mr Justice Aikens]] and [[Nigel Davis|Mr Justice Davis]], ruled that Childs' evidence against the pair was unreliable because he was a "pathological liar".<ref name="overturned">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/essex/3320845.stm|title=Murder convictions overturned|date=15 December 2003|work=BBC News|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> |- |1975 |[[Stefan Kiszko]] |Rape and murder of a girl |Rishworth Moor, West Yorkshire |Life |16 Years |1992 |[[Stefan Kiszko]] was convicted in 1976 for the [[Murder of Lesley Molseed|rape and murder of an 11-year-old Lesley Molseed]] in 1975. He spent 16 years in prison before he was released in 1992, after a long campaign by his mother. He died of a heart attack the following year at the age of 41. His mother died a few months later. In 2007, [[Murder of Lesley Molseed|Ronald Castree]], of Shaw, near Oldham, was arrested on [[DNA]] evidence, was convicted of Molseed's murder at Bradford Crown Court and jailed for life. |- |1977 |[[Robert Brown case|Robert Brown]] |Murder of a woman |[[Hulme, Manchester|Hulme]], [[Manchester]] |Life |25 years |Yes |Brown was convicted in 1977 of the murder of 51 year old Annie Walsh at her flat in Hulme, Greater Manchester. Despite numerous appeals, Brown's conviction was only declared 'unsafe' in 2002, when three appeal court judges heard how his confession was beaten out of him, the forensic evidence pointed to someone else and